<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-416-221  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 416 221.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>3 Legion of Doom members plead guilty to computer fraud.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   BellSouth Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    BLS.andO;Topic:     Computer crimesComputer hackersCourt Cases.andO;Person:    Grant, Adam E. (cases); Darden, Franklin Jr. (cases); Riggs,Robert J. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>3 LEGION OF DOOM MEMBERS PLEAD GUILTY TO COMPUTER FRAUD ATLANTA, GEORGIA,U.S.A., 1990 JUL 10 (NB) -- Federal law enforcement officials have announcedthat three members of the so-called Legion-of-Doom computer group havepleaded guilty to various charges surrounding computer break-ins toBellSouth's systems.andM;The individuals, Adam E. Grant, Franklin Darden, Jr.andP;  and Robert J. Riggs,were charged with conspiracy to commit computer fraud, wire fraud, accesscode fraud and transport stolen property across state lines during the periodSeptember 10, 1987 through July 21, 1989.andM;Darden and Riggs each pleaded guilty to one conspiracy count and can receiveup to a maximum sentence of five years in prison and a $200,000 fine.andP;  Grantpleaded guilty to possessing 15 or more BellSouth access devices with theintent to defraud and faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a$250,000 fine.andM;Sentencing is scheduled for September 14th and Ken Alexander, assistant U.S.andO;attorney, told Newsbytes that the plea agreement holds out the possibility ofreduced sentences.andP;  &quot;The plea agreement allows the United States Attorney'soffice to, in return for substantial assistance from the defendants, to askfor a downward departure from the sentencing guidelines.andP;  The substantialassistance referred to includes debriefing by the Secret Service and truthfultestimony in other related computer cases.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/199000711)</TEXT></DOC>